/*!

  \page src_HLS_page High-Level Synthesis

  This page is organized as follows:
  - \ref HLS_overview presents the general outlines of the high-level synthesis problem.
  - \ref HLS_problem defines the problem in a formal way.
  - \ref HLS_bambu describes how informations are stored in the Bambu tool and how they can be retrieved.

  \section HLS_overview High-Level Synthesis overview

  High-level synthesis (HLS) is the design activity that translates a behavioral specification into a hardware implementation at
  register-transfer level (RTL). The purpose of HLS is to automate the construction of datapaths, controllers, storage structures,
  and interconnect starting from a program-like description while still exposing meaningful optimization trade-offs to the designer.

  HLS sits between the software-oriented view of an algorithm and the lower-level hardware implementation steps that follow RTL generation.
  A practical HLS flow must therefore combine compiler-style analyses, architectural decisions, and technology-aware cost models.

  This is the role of the HLS infrastructure in PandA Bambu: starting from the PandA internal representation of the input program,
  the flow analyzes dependencies and memory behavior, schedules operations, allocates and binds resources, and finally emits the structural RTL representation consumed by back-end tools.

  \subsection sec_synthesis The synthesis process

<I><B>Synthesis</B></I> is the generation of a circuit model, starting
from a less detailed one. Models can be classified in terms of levels of abstraction
and views. We consider here three main abstractions, namely: <i>architectural</I>, <I>logic</I> and
<I>geometrical</I>. The levels can he visualized as follows. At the <i>architectural level</I> a circuit
performs a set of operations, such as data computation or transfer. At the <I>logic level</I>,
a digital circuit evaluates a set of logic functions. At the <I>geometrical level</I>, a circuit
is a set of geometrical entities. 


The architectural-level synthesis consists of generating a structural view of an architectural-level model. This corresponds to determining an assignment of the circuit
functions to operators, called resources, as well as their interconnection and the
timing of their execution. It has also been called <b>high-level synthesis</B> or <B>structural synthesis</B>, because it determines the macroscopic (i.e., block-level) structure of the circuit. A behavioral architectural-level model can be abstracted as a set of operations and dependencies. Architectural synthesis entails identifying the hardware resources that can implement the operations, scheduling the execution time of the operations and binding them to the resources. In other words, synthesis defines a structural model of a data path, as an interconnection of resources, and a logic-level model of a control unit, that issues the control signals to the data path according to the schedule.
After the architectural-level synthesis, the <i>logic-level synthesis</I> step has to be performed. Logic-level synthesis is the task of generating a structural view of a logic-level
model. Logic synthesis is the manipulation of logic specifications to create logic
models as an interconnection of logic primitives. Thus logic synthesis determines
the microscopic (i.e., gate-level) structure of a circuit. The task of transforming a
logic model into an interconnection of instances of library cells, i.e., the back end
of logic synthesis, is often referred to as library binding or technology mapping.
A logic-level model of a circuit can be provided by a state transition diagram of a finite-state machine, by a circuit schematic or equivalently by an HDL model. It may be specified by a designer or synthesized from an architectural-level model.
The logic synthesis tasks may be different according to the nature of the circuit
(e.g., sequential or combinational) and to the initial representation (e.g., state diagram
or schematic). Since many are the possible configurations of a circuit, optimization plays
a major role, in connection with synthesis, in determining the microscopic figures
of merit of the implementation. The final outcome of logic synthesis is a fully structural representation, such as a gate-level netlist.
The final step is the <I>geometrical-level synthesis</I>, that consists of creating a physical view at the geometric level. It entails the specification of all geometric patterns defining the physical
layout of the chip, as well as their position. It is often called physical design, and
we shall call it so. Physical design consists of generating the layout of the chip.
The layers of the layout are in correspondence with the masks used for chip fabrication.
Therefore, the geometrical layout is the final target of microelectronic circuit design.
Physical design depends much on the design style. On one end of the spectrum, for
custom design, physical design is handcrafted by using layout editors. This means
that the designer renounces the use of automated synthesis tools in the search for
optimizing the circuit geometries by fine hand-tuning. On the opposite end of the
spectrum, in case of prewired circuits, physical design is performed in a virtual
fashion, because chips are fully manufactured in advance. 
The major tasks in physical design are placement and wiring, called also routing. Cell generation is essential in the particular case of macro-cell design, where cells are synthesized and not extracted from a library.

Logic-level and physical synthesis are already heavily automated by downstream toolchains, but they expect RTL as input.
HLS bridges that gap by generating RTL from a behavioral specification while still accounting for timing, area, power, memory organization,
resource sharing, and implementation constraints.


  \section HLS_problem Problem description

<i>High-Level Synthesis</I> (HLS) is defined as a translation process from 
behavioural description into register-transfer-level (RTL) structural description. It can be considered the 
automation of first step of the design flow, the architectural-level synthesis.


The inputs to a typical HLS tool include a <I>behavioral description</I>, 
a <I>resource library</I> describing available hardware resources and a set 
of <I>design constraints</I>.

The output from a high-level synthesizer consists of two parts: a datapath 
structure at the register-transfer level (RTL) and a specification of the finite 
state machine to control the datapath. At the RTL level, a datapath is composed 
of functional units, storage and interconnection elements. The finite state 
machine specifies every set of microoperations for the datapath to be performed 
during each control step. The output can be then synthesized using related tools.

The goal is to reduce one or more design targets. Objectives can be to minimize 
total area occupied, latency or power consumption.

<I>Behavioral description</I> specifies behaviour in terms of operations,
assignment statements, and control constructs in a common high-level language.
Within Bambu, this information is represented through the internal IR and the analysis data structures built on top of it.

In the <I>resource library</I>, there may be several alternatives
among which the synthesizer must select the one that best matches the design
constraints and maximizes the optimization objective.

The <I>constraints</I> can be on the maximum number of available units of each resource,
on total area, throughput, clock period, or on the latency of the specification execution.

There are two main tasks in high-level synthesis: operations scheduling and resources 
allocation. <I>Scheduling</i> provides the control steps in which 
operations start their execution (see \ref src_HLS_scheduling_general). <I>Resource allocation</I> (see \ref src_HLS_module_allocation and \ref src_HLS_binding_page)
is concerned with assigning operations and values to hardware components and 
interconnect them using connection elements. Solving these problems efficiently is 
a non-trivial matter because of their NP-complete nature. Furthermore, the objectives are usually in contrast and the 
best high-level synthesis design flow cannot be known a priori since it depends heavily 
on nature of the problem: on some examples, executing scheduling before allocation can leads to better results, on other examples, it can leads to worse ones.

The remaining task is the creation of the structural representation of the datapath and the controller units, including the finite-state-machine controller described in \ref src_HLS_fsm.


  \section HLS_bambu Data structures in the Bambu tool


   "Scheduling assigns operations in the behavioral description to
   control steps. Within each control step, a separate functional unit is 
   required to execute each operation assigned to that step.
    
   After scheduling, the datapath is constructed in two steps: 
   unit allocation and unit binding; some researchers call unit allocation and 
   unit binding collectively as datapath allocation. 
   Unit allocation determines the number and types of RT components to be used 
   in the design. Since a real RT component library may contain multiple types 
   of functional units, each with different characteristics (e.g., 
   functionality, size, delay and power dissipation), unit allocation needs to 
   determine the number and types of different functional and storage units 
   present in the component library. Unit binding maps the operations, variables, 
   and data transfers from the scheduled CDFG to the functional, storage and 
   interconnection units, respectively, while ensuring that the design 
   behavior operates correctly on the selected set of components. 
   Unit binding consists of three interdependent tasks: storage binding, functional-unit 
   binding, and interconnection binding.
   Storage binding maps data carriers (e.g., constants, variables and data 
   structures like arrays) in the behavioral description onto storage 
   elements (e.g., ROMs, registers and memory units) in the datapath. 
   Functional-unit binding involves the mapping of operations in the 
   behavioral description to the set of selected functional units. 
   Interconnection binding maps every data transfer in the behavior into a 
   set of interconnection units for data routing"[1].

  In Bambu these concepts are reflected in a set of shared HLS data structures that are progressively populated by the synthesis flow.
  The central container is the \c hls structure declared in \c src/HLS/hls.hpp. It stores the current synthesis state for one function,
  including the target device and constraints (\c HLS_D and \c HLS_C), the scheduling and binding results (\c Rsch, \c Rfu, \c Rreg, \c Rconn),
  the FSM metadata (\c fsm_info), and the structural RTL descriptions (\c datapath, \c controller, and \c top).
  The following sections summarize the main phases and the state produced by each of them.

  \subsection src_HLS_hls_structure Current hls structure overview
  The \c hls struct is the canonical entry point for the current flow. Key members include:
  - \c functionId, which identifies the function being implemented so diagnostics can trace synthesized artifacts back to the original behavioral input.
  - \c module_binding_algorithm, \c chaining_algorithm, and \c liveVariableAlgorithm, each typed as \c HLSFlowStep_Type and recording the variant chosen for module binding, chaining, and live-variable analysis.
  - \c operations, the \c OpVertexSet that holds the subset of specification operations targeted by this synthesis run.
  - \c HLS_D and \c HLS_C, referencing \c HLS_device and \c HLS_constraints, respectively, so device pins and constraints remain tied to the flow state.
  - \c allocation_information (\c AllocationInformationRef), \c Rsch (\c Schedule), \c Rfu (\c fu_binding), \c Rreg / \c RregGroup (\c reg_binding), \c Rconn (\c conn_binding), and \c chaining_information (\c ChainingInformation), which materialize the progressively populated scheduling, binding, and chaining results.
  - \c Rliv (\c liveVariablesRef), \c storage_value_information (\c StorageValueInformation), and \c call_sites_number, which track live-variable sets, storage metadata, and the number of call sites considered for the current function.
  - \c registered_inputs and \c registered_done_port, which flag whether the synthesized top module exposes registered handshake inputs or a registered done signal.
  - \c datapath, \c controller, and \c top, each a \c structural_manager describing the synthesized structural RTL for datapath, controller, and top-level composition.
  - \c Param (\c ParameterConstRef), \c debug_level, \c output_level, and \c HLS_execution_time, which control verbosity and record how long the HLS flow took to complete.

  \section src_HLS_phases Phases 
  - Subproject \ref src_HLS_scheduling_general provides scheduling algorithms.
  - Module allocation provides facilities for functional unit allocation.
  - Subproject \ref src_HLS_binding_constraints_page provides facilities for operation binding on functional units
  - Subproject \ref src_HLS_binding_page provides synthesis algorithms about register allocation, module binding optimization and interconnetion allocation.
  - Datapath construction creates the structural representation of the datapath.
  - Subproject \ref src_HLS_fsm creates structural representation about controller
  - The HLS flow coordinates the end-to-end high-level synthesis pipeline.

  \section src_HLS_additional Additional subprojects 
  - Estimation components provide metrics and reports for synthesized results.

  \section src_HLS_data_structure Data structures
  This section describes the data structures used in High Level Synthesis algorithm.
  Typically a High Level Synthesis task is divided in four stages and our algorithm follows
  this division:
  - Scheduling and functional unit binding;
  - Register Binding;
  - Interconnection Binding;
  - Datapath and Controller generation. \n

  For each of these stages, the \c hls structure exposes dedicated fields. For scheduling
  and functional-unit assignment, the main objects are:
  - \c Rsch, an instance of class \c Schedule declared in \c src/HLS/scheduling/schedule.hpp;
  - \c Rfu, an instance of class \c fu_binding declared in \c src/HLS/binding/module/fu_binding.hpp. \n

  For storage and register binding, the main object is:
  - \c Rreg, an instance of class \c reg_binding declared in \c src/HLS/binding/register/reg_binding.hpp. \n

  For interconnection binding and controller/datapath construction, the main objects are:
  - \c Rconn, an instance of class \c conn_binding declared in \c src/HLS/binding/interconnection/conn_binding.hpp;
  - \c fsm_info, an instance of class \c FSMInfo declared in \c src/HLS/fsm/FSMInfo.hpp;
  - \c datapath, \c controller, and \c top, which are structural descriptions built as \c structural_manager instances. \n

  These structures are described in more detail in the next sections.
  \subsection src_HLS_data_structure_scheduling Scheduling data structures
  Scheduling state is no longer described as a pair of ad-hoc variables such as \c sch and \c fu.
  In the current codebase it is encapsulated by dedicated classes stored inside the \c hls structure.

  \subsubsection src_HLS_schedule Schedule
  The \c Rsch field stores a \c Schedule object.
  As documented in \c src/HLS/scheduling/schedule.hpp, this object records:
  - the control step in which each operation starts and ends;
  - absolute control steps represented through \c AbsControlStep;
  - absolute start and end times for scheduled operations;
  - connection timing information;
  - loop pipelining metadata such as initiation interval information.

  This is the authoritative scheduling state used by downstream phases such as FSM construction, chaining, and resource reporting.

  \subsubsection src_HLS_fu_binding Current functional-unit assignment
  The \c Rfu field stores a \c fu_binding object.
  It records, for each scheduled operation, both the selected functional-unit kind and the specific instance used to execute that operation.
  Together, \c Rsch and \c Rfu define the executable timing/resource view consumed by later HLS phases.

  \subsection src_HLS_data_structure_binding Register binding data structures
  Register binding is represented by class \c reg_binding rather than by legacy variables such as \c bind, \c bind_const, \c used_reg, and \c used_const.

  \subsubsection src_HLS_reg_binding Register binding
  The \c Rreg field stores a \c reg_binding object declared in \c src/HLS/binding/register/reg_binding.hpp.
  This object maps storage values to register objects, tracks the number of used registers, stores reverse mappings from storage values to register indices,
  records register bitwidths, and keeps auxiliary information needed for context switches and write-enable handling.

  When present, \c RregGroup stores an additional grouping view over register resources.
  These objects are the stable data structures to inspect when reasoning about storage allocation in the current code.

  \subsection src_HLS_data_structure_datapath Interconnection binding data structures
  \subsubsection src_HLS_conn_binding Interconnection binding
  The \c Rconn field stores a \c conn_binding object declared in \c src/HLS/binding/interconnection/conn_binding.hpp.
  This object manages the connection-level view of the datapath, including:
  - source-to-target connection descriptions;
  - activation and selector ports;
  - constant values and converters;
  - the mapping between connection endpoints and their structural implementation.

  \subsubsection src_HLS_datapath_struct Datapath structure
  The \c datapath field stores the structural description of the datapath as a \c structural_manager.
  This representation contains components, channels, signals, ports, and interfaces after scheduling, storage binding, and interconnection binding have been resolved.

  \subsection src_HLS_data_structure_fsm Controller creation
  \subsubsection src_HLS_fsm_info FSM metadata
  The \c fsm_info field stores an instance of \c FSMInfo declared in \c src/HLS/fsm/FSMInfo.hpp.
  This object holds the metadata used to build and inspect the controller, including:
  - state descriptors and transition metadata;
  - operations starting, executing, or ending in each state;
  - basic-block to state relationships;
  - loop-pipelining metadata attached to states and transitions.

  \subsubsection src_HLS_controller_struct Controller structure
  The \c controller field stores the structural description of the synthesized controller as a \c structural_manager.
  The \c top field stores the final top-level structural composition that couples controller and datapath.

  \subsection src_HLS_data_structure_other Other data structure
  This section historically described a set of global maps used to couple controller and datapath generation.
  In the current codebase these details are distributed across the binding classes, \c FSMInfo, and the structural managers rather than being exposed as a single stable public API.

  For practical inspection and debugging, the most relevant entry points today are:
  - \c hls::print(), \c hls::PrintScheduling(), \c hls::print_register_binding(), and \c hls::print_connection_binding() in \c src/HLS/hls.hpp;
  - the scheduling state stored in \c Schedule;
  - the storage and interconnection state stored in \c reg_binding and \c conn_binding;
  - the controller-state metadata stored in \c FSMInfo.

  When updating or extending the HLS flow, these classes should be treated as the source of truth for the current synthesis state.
  Documentation that assumes the existence of fixed maps such as \c input_enable_port, \c input_address_port, \c in_port_map, or \c out_port_map should be considered legacy unless it is explicitly reintroduced and documented in the code.

